    "title": "Circulation Emergencies5",
    "content": "\"Soft Signs\" of a Heart Attack During a heart attack, many females, elderly people, and people with diabetes tend to experience \"soft signs,\" which are milder or more generalized than the \"classic\" signs and symptoms of a heart attack. These \"soft signs\" may be experienced for hours, days, or even weeks prior to the heart attack and are often dismissed as nothing out of the \"Soft signs\" include: • Mild, unfocused chest discomfort that: ¶Comes and goes ¶Does not necessarily feel painful ¶Gets better with rest and worse with activity, or gets progressively worse • Extreme fatigue (tiredness) • Gastric discomfort, nausea, or vomiting • Flu-like symptoms • Dizziness or light-headedness What to Do If you suspect a person is having a heart attack, call EMS/9-1-1 and get an AED immediately. 3. If the person takes a prescribed medication to relieve chest pain (e.g., nitroglycerin), offer to locate the medication and help the person to take it. • If the person has nitroglycerin in a spray or pill form, ensure that the person sprays or places the nitroglycerin under his or her tongue. 4. Reassure the person. Anxiety may increase the person’s discomfort.Care 1. Have the person rest comfortably. 2. If acetylsalicylic acid (ASA) is available, encourage the person to chew 160 to 325 mg (either 1 adult-dose or 2 low-dose ASA tablets), unless the person has an allergy or a contraindication to ASA, such as a bleeding disorder. Ensure that the person thoroughly chews and swallows the ASA. Do not repeat the Not everyone experiences chest pain during a heart attack. Circulation Emergencies52.",
